For those who suffer this while jobless, my 2.5 cents:

Life was a total mess squared. I tried a few tricks (todo list, sleep schedule, diet, exercise, fengshui). At best the results were ridicule.. or would fade at the slightest issue.

I then got a stupid job, and I noticed how the forces of society are infinitely (hyperbole) stronger than my own desire.

- job makes me owe duty and presence to others, and I cannot escape it because the blame and stigma (can be a problem but in this case it's good)

- global rhythm enforced for free, wake up earlier, eat at regular pace, come home happy to leave the job, often calm (if your job doesn't follow you home), eager to eat, eager to sleep

- sense of priority, you care less about side things and more about a few things that will either benefit your job or benefit your time home. it filters a ton of itches

- less anxiety, you're like everybody, you can follow the flow of life, it lifts a huge weight of your shoulders and give you a lot more focus and motivation than before so sometimes you can start more stuff but you know your time and energy budget, less struggle.

peace

May I share the issues that made me run away from the field:

- lack of clear social value / beauty (money isn't everything)[0]

- high frequency randomness in some areas (never ending change of context and tools)

- difficulty of finding a think-team to discuss issues instead of grinding alone in a cubicle

If people share this, tell me, if others have more factors, tell me too.

[0] I find more pleasure serving pastry .. it's trivial but the ratio simple / people pleasure / shared interaction is high

for simple setups (like mine) arch is stable. People who had issues were often using slightly advanced hardware setup (proprietary gpus, multi gpus)... 

I can count breakage on one hand, and 3 of them were me not monitoring archlinux.org because everything was explained there. One was resolved in a minute on IRC and the last one was a weird state of CA certs I never understood but alas.

ps: used arch since single-config-file days mostly as my main distro, but my usage is frugal: i3/dwm/xmonad firefox emacs mpv (then dev things gcc haskell python forth prolog malbolge brainfuck, the usual)

Si c'est une question de carriere et de niveau de vie, chose qu'on a pas forcement en etant caissier alors peut-etre tu peux tenter un intermediaire. Si t'as un bon reseau tu peux juste faire freelance a temps partiel pour te garantir un mensuel decent et le reste tu fais des trucs chill mais agreable.

En general si tu fais les choses 'naturellement' bonnes, tu t'endors le soir en te disant 'vivement demain' sans meme y penser. C'est un peu comme un couple ..

[0] soit j'arrive a resoudre les trucs seul de facon belle et la satisfaction est un bonus (sinon c'est l'angoisse) soit il me faut une team soudee avec qui je peux brainstormer d'egal a egal.. mais ca ca m'est arrive que trop rarement. 

[1] j'ai peu d'experience mais j'ai jamais trouve de mission dont le but me plaisait.. les ESN t'envoies chez TF1 pour refaire leur systeme de programmation tele.. rigolo mais pas passionnant.
